  {
    "id": 5,
    "title": "AI & Robotics Snacks — April 3, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-03",
    "tags": [
      "Anthropic",
      "Microsoft",
      "OpenAI",
      "TBPN",
      "Gemini",
      "Claude Mythos 5"
    ],
    "fresh": true,
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 3, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 💰 Anthropic Is Now Worth $380 Billion (Totally Normal Number)\n\nWhile everyone was watching OpenAI burn cash, Anthropic quietly closed a **$30 billion Series G** led by GIC and Coatue, valuing the company at **$380 billion post-money**. For reference: that's more than McDonald's, Caterpillar, and most European automakers combined. For a company that started as a group of people who left OpenAI over safety disagreements.\n\n- Q1 2026 foundational AI startup funding doubled *all of 2025*. The money spigot hasn't been turned off — it's been welded open.\n- $380B for a company that hasn't IPO'd yet. Investors are, apparently, fine with all of this.\n\n*Nobody builds a $380B company and just chills. Whatever Anthropic is building next, the check has already cleared.*\n\n**Sources:** [Crunchbase: Q1 2026 AI VC funding](https://news.crunchbase.com/venture/foundational-ai-startup-funding-doubled-openai-anthropic-xai-q1-2026/) | [Mean CEO: AI Startup Funding April 2026](https://blog.mean.ceo/ai-startup-funding-news-april-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 The Benchmark War: Gemini 3.1 Pro vs Claude Mythos 5 (It's Getting Weird)\n\nGPT-5.4 is barely a week old and already getting flanked. Google launched **Gemini 3.1 Pro**, which leads **13 out of 16 major benchmarks** and ties GPT-5.4 Pro on the Artificial Analysis Intelligence Index — at roughly **one-third the API cost**. Not to be outweighed literally, Anthropic dropped **Claude Mythos 5** with **10 trillion parameters**, aimed at cybersecurity and coding.\n\n- Gemini 3.1 Pro: top-tier benchmark performance at a third of the price. Google would like you to know that running your own infrastructure at planetary scale has advantages.\n- Claude Mythos 5 has 10x more parameters than GPT-4. Anthropic released this with roughly the fanfare of a software patch.\n- The models are getting cheaper and more capable simultaneously. We're not sure what happens next either.\n\n**Sources:** [Mean CEO: New AI Model Releases April 2026](https://blog.mean.ceo/new-ai-model-releases-news-april-2026/) | [RenovateQR: AI Models April 2026](https://renovateqr.com/blog/ai-models-april-2026)\n\n---\n\n## 🎙️ OpenAI Bought a Podcast and Called It \"Strategy\"\n\nOpenAI acquired **TBPN**, a daily tech talk show with 58,000 YouTube subscribers, for \"low hundreds of millions\" according to the Financial Times. The podcast made $5M in ad revenue in 2025 and is projecting $30M this year. It will sit inside OpenAI's Strategy org under Chris Lehane — OpenAI's head of policy — and maintain \"editorial independence.\" Sure.\n\n- \"Editorial independence\" at a media company just acquired by its most prominent subject of coverage. Fine. Probably fine.\n- Sam Altman has been a featured guest. Sam Altman's company now owns the show. Sam Altman will presumably keep appearing. (Checks out.)\n- OpenAI is burning $14B annually and spending nine figures on a podcast. Prioritization is hard.\n\n*Nobody asked \"what if we just owned the media that covers us?\" and yet here we are.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch: OpenAI acquires TBPN](https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/02/openai-acquires-tbpn-the-buzzy-founder-led-business-talk-show/) | [CNBC: OpenAI acquires TBPN](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/04/02/openai-acquires-tech-podcast-tbpn.html)\n\n---\n\n## 🏗️ Microsoft Just Bet $10 Billion on Japan (Sakura Internet Is Up 20%)\n\nMicrosoft announced a **$10 billion, four-year investment** in Japan for AI infrastructure and cybersecurity, partnering with SoftBank, Sakura Internet, NTT Data, NEC, Fujitsu, and Hitachi. Goal: train **1 million AI professionals by 2030**. Sakura Internet's stock jumped **20%** in a single session.\n\n- This is part of a broader Microsoft Asia push — the logic being that you want datacenters in stable jurisdictions before trade wars get significantly weirder.\n- Training 1 million AI professionals is either a serious workforce commitment or an extremely good excuse to sell a lot of Azure Copilot licenses. Possibly both.\n- Japan gets AI infrastructure. Microsoft gets a geopolitical hedge. SoftBank gets a partner announcement. Sakura Internet gets a 20% pop. Everybody wins, apparently.\n\n**Sources:** [Bloomberg: Microsoft $10B Japan investment](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-03/microsoft-drafts-10-billion-investment-plan-in-ai-hungry-japan) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/microsoft-to-invest-10-billion-in-japan-for-ai-and-cyber-defence-expansion-4596854)"
  },
  {
    "id": 4,
    "title": "AI Newz Snacks — April 2, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-02",
    "tags": [
      "OpenAI",
      "Huawei",
      "Atlassian",
      "Sakana AI",
      "Robots"
    ],
    "fresh": false,
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 2, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 💸 OpenAI Burns $14B a Year and Is Now Worth More Than Boeing\n\nCongratulations to OpenAI, which just crossed **$25 billion in annualized revenue** — a milestone achieved while simultaneously projecting $14 billion in losses for 2026. The company is reportedly taking early steps toward a public listing, potentially as soon as late 2026. Investors are, apparently, fine with all of this.\n\n- For context: OpenAI makes $2B a month and loses more than that. They're basically a nonprofit with delusions of grandeur and everyone loves them for it.\n- The IPO path means we get to watch the market assign a valuation to a company that burns cash faster than it earns it. Gonna be a fun roadshow.\n- Meanwhile, GPT is testing ads. Because what screams \"future of humanity\" more than banner ads on your AI assistant?\n\n**Sources:** [Mean CEO AI News April 2026](https://blog.mean.ceo/ai-news-april-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 AI Wrote a Research Paper That Fooled Peer Reviewers (Cool, Great)\n\nOh great, another thing AI is better at now. Sakana AI's \"AI Scientist\" submitted a research paper to a prestigious ML conference and it **passed peer review**. The system generated the idea, ran the experiments, wrote the paper, and reviewed itself. The peer reviewers did not notice.\n\n- This is either a triumph of AI capability or a damning indictment of peer review, and honestly it might be both simultaneously.\n- Before you panic: the paper was apparently mediocre. So peer review is fine with mediocrity from a robot. Completely on brand.\n- The researchers were upfront that this was an experiment in AI-driven science. The reviewers were... less upfront about spotting it.\n\n**Sources:** [Mean CEO AI News April 2026](https://blog.mean.ceo/ai-news-april-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🇨🇳 Huawei's New AI Chip Just Got Massive Orders (The Sanctions Are Going Great)\n\nShocker: trying to cut China off from Nvidia chips just made China build its own. Huawei launched the **950PR AI chip** optimized for inference workloads, and ByteDance and Alibaba have reportedly placed **large orders**. Mass production starts this month, 750,000 chips planned for H2 2026.\n\n- The 950PR goes for 50,000–70,000 yuan per chip ($7-10K). Not cheap, but it's domestic, tariff-proof, and increasingly \"good enough.\"\n- The grand plan to kneecap China's AI progress is going exactly as expected: they made their own chips and are now ordering them at scale. Cool strategy.\n- ByteDance and Alibaba collectively have more computing demand than most G7 governments. Huawei found a customer.\n\n**Sources:** [CNBC: ByteDance and Alibaba ordering Huawei's new AI chip](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/03/27/bytedance-alibaba-planning-to-order-huaweis-new-ai-chip-reuters.html)\n\n---\n\n## ✂️ Atlassian Just Fired 1,600 People to Hire AI Instead\n\nWho would've thought that the company that makes the software engineers use to track software engineering work would cut 10% of its workforce to... build more AI? Atlassian announced layoffs of approximately **1,600 employees** to redirect resources toward AI development.\n\n- The framing is \"investing in the future.\" The reality is that Jira is going to be maintained by fewer humans and more copilots. Somehow this feels inevitable.\n- Atlassian joins a growing list of companies that have discovered that \"AI investments\" and \"human employees\" are now in direct competition for the same budget line.\n- The laid-off workers can find work training the humanoid robots that will replace the AI teams that just replaced them. Circle of life.\n\n**Sources:** [Mean CEO AI News April 2026](https://blog.mean.ceo/ai-news-april-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🦾 Europe's Humanoid Rush: BMW Has Robots Now, Apparently\n\nNot to be left out of the humanoid arms race, Europe is quietly deploying. Sweden's **Hexagon AB** is testing humanoid robots at industrial clients including **BMW**, while **Realbotix** is delivering 19 humanoid robots to various sites through May 2026 as production scales.\n\n- Hexagon does industrial measurement and software. Now they also do bipedal robots. This feels like a pivot.\n- BMW — already running highly automated factories — is apparently asking \"but what if the automation also had legs?\" Reasonable question, honestly.\n- 19 robots is not a lot. But nobody started the internet with 19 websites and thought \"nah, too small.\"\n\n**Sources:** [Robotics Tomorrow: Realbotix delivery update](https://www.roboticstomorrow.com/news/2026/04/01/realbotix-provides-ai-humanoid-robot-delivery-update/26349/)\n\n---\n\n## 📌 Sources\n\n- [Mean CEO: AI News April 2026](https://blog.mean.ceo/ai-news-april-2026/)\n- [CNBC: Huawei 950PR chip orders](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/03/27/bytedance-alibaba-planning-to-order-huaweis-new-ai-chip-reuters.html)\n- [Robotics Tomorrow: Realbotix humanoid update](https://www.roboticstomorrow.com/news/2026/04/01/realbotix-provides-ai-humanoid-robot-delivery-update/26349/)\n"
  },
